      <h2 class='section' id='what_is_origin'>What is origin?</h2>

<p>This is your content, your meat &amp; potatoes. The <a href='http://www.w3.org/TR/2011/WD-html5-20110525/'>HTML5 spec</a> introduced the idea of <em>aria roles</em>, and all of your &#8220;content&#8221; has the aria role of <code>main</code>, which functions as the main content of a document.</p>

<p><a class='button' href='http://www.w3.org/TR/2011/WD-html5-20110525/'><em>See</em> the HTML5 Spec</a></p>

<p>This marks the content that is directly related to or expands upon the central topic of the document. The main role is a non-obtrusive alternative for &#8220;skip to main content&#8221; links, where the navigation option to go to the main content (or other landmarks) is provided by the user agent through a dialog or by assistive technologies. User agents SHOULD treat elements with the role of main as navigational landmarks. Within any document or application, the author SHOULD mark no more than one element with the main role.</p>

<h2 class='section' id='blockquotes'>Blockquotes</h2>

<p>Blockquotes are styled to be clean, readable, with a nice callout.</p>

<blockquote>
<p><em>We cannot teach people anything; we can only help them discover it within themselves.</em><br /><strong class='tertiary'>- Galileo</strong></p>
</blockquote>

<p>Then we continue on our rant.</p>

<h2 class='section' id='code_blocks'>Code Blocks</h2>

<p>Why not some example <a href='http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/JavaScript'>JS</a>?</p>

<pre><code>// let&#39;s look at some javascript&#x000A;$(document).ready(function(){&#x000A;  var say = &#39;word.&#39;;&#x000A;  console.log(say) // oops, no semicolon.&#x000A;});</code></pre>

<p>See how I omitted that semi-colon there? Also, did I mention origin has baked in code highlighting using prettify JS?</p>

